## CSS Class Naming: camelCase Only

All CSS class names in this project use **camelCase**. Never use kebab-case or snake_case.

### HTML / Svelte templates
```svelte
<!-- ✅ Correct -->
<div class="bookingCard fieldGroup">
<button class="btnPrimary btnLg">

<!-- ❌ Wrong -->
<div class="booking-card field-group">
<button class="btn-primary btn-lg">
```

### Svelte class directives
```svelte
<!-- ✅ Correct -->
<tr class:nearlyFull={slot.remaining <= 1}>

<!-- ❌ Wrong -->
<tr class:nearly-full={slot.remaining <= 1}>
```

### CSS selectors (in `<style>` blocks and `.css` files)
```css
/* ✅ Correct */
.bookingCard { ... }
.tableRow.statusCancelled { ... }

/* ❌ Wrong */
.booking-card { ... }
.table-row.status-cancelled { ... }
```

### Dynamic classes from runtime values
Use a lookup map — never build kebab-case strings via interpolation:
```svelte
<script>
  // ✅ Map runtime values to camelCase class names
  const badgeClass: Record<string, string> = {
    pending: 'badgePending',
    confirmed: 'badgeConfirmed',
    cancelled: 'badgeCancelled'
  };
</script>

<!-- ✅ Correct -->
<span class="badge {badgeClass[item.status]}">

<!-- ❌ Wrong -->
<span class="badge badge-{item.status}">
```
